title: For Sale:  Chinese Military Type 54 Tokarev Pistol
postcontent:
I'm a private collector and, as part of a multi-gun lot in a recent auction, picked up an excellent Type 54 semiauto pistol in 7.62 x 25 Tokarev.  (Or, as the Chinese would call it, 54式手枪).  It shows no wear from carry or use but doesn’t fit in with the rest of my collection, so I’m offering it for sale.  

This gun was made in the 1950’s by the state armory in the Peoples Republic of China (Norinco) for the Red Army.  It is a faithful copy of the Tokarev pistol designed by China’s then-ally, the USSR, with exception of an added safety to allow cocked-and-locked carry (never carry an original design Russian Tokarev with a round in the chamber).  

This gun is lightweight and well-balanced.  I’ve not fired this gun, but the ammunition choices are said to be varied and even quite fun!  Conventional 7.62 x 25 ammo is available from most of the major internet ammo sellers.  But you can also get green or red tracer ammo for low-light shooting.  Although the Type 54 is dated by contemporary military standards, this is said to be the most popular handgun among organized crime figures in Asia as the ammo available overseas is hot enough to defeat body armor.  

Face-to-face sale not possible, but I’ll ship to a FFL-holder/firearms retailer near you for $20 or deliver to an FFL-holder in the NW Chicago suburbs for free.  Payment by money order or personal check is okay; just enclose a copy of the FFL license with your payment.  Item will be shipped only to the address on the license.  I have an FFL (03) license (the “curio and relic collector” license) and will send a copy of my license when shipping the gun.  Make sure your retailer is okay with accepting a shipment from an FFL (03) holder  

Call REDACTED or contact by me via email at REDACTED.  (Please call only between 9 a.m. and 9 p. m. Central Time).

title: For Sale:  Ideal, low cost home defense revolver:  Llama Ruby Extra .38 Special
postcontent:
Excellent condition.  I'm a private collector and, as part of a multi-gun lot in a recent auction, picked up an excellent .38 Special revolver.  It doesn’t fit in with the rest of my collection, so I’m offering it for sale, but not before testing it thoroughly at my local range. It is in great shape; is spot-on accurate; and will be an excellent, low-cost self-defense or carry gun for a new owner.   As the saying goes: “A revolver never lets you down!”

The revolver is a Llama Ruby Extra, made in the 1960s in Spain by the Llama-Gabilondo y Cia company to compete globally with Smith & Wesson’s Model 10 as a police issue sidearm.  This Llama has features that actually make it nicer than the Smith & Wesson police gun, including a grooved backstrap for a better grip and a grooved top strap to cut down on haze in the sight radius.  

The Llama Ruby Extra sold well to police departments in South America and the Philippines but this one must have been shipped directly to the US as it is not import-marked.  The bore/lands/grooves are in great condition and the gun has just a trace of finish wear at the muzzle, so it seems to have spent more time in a sock drawer than a holster.  

Face-to-face sale not possible, but I’ll ship to a FFL-holder/firearms retailer near you for $20 or deliver to an FFL-holder in the NW Chicago suburbs for free.  Payment by money order or personal check is okay; just enclose a copy of the FFL license with your payment.  Item will be shipped only to the address on the license.  I have an FFL (03) license (the “curio and relic collector” license) and will send a copy of my license when shipping the gun.
